{
  "What creates a magnetic field?": "",
  "Moving electric charges or electric currents": "",
  "Thermal energy": "",
  "Gravitational forces": "",
  "Stationary electric charges": "",
  "Magnetic fields are produced by moving electric charges (currents). Even permanent magnets derive their magnetism from the motion of electrons within their atoms.": "",
  "The SI unit of magnetic field strength is the:": "",
  "Tesla": "",
  "Volt": "",
  "Coulomb": "",
  "Ampere": "",
  "The SI unit of magnetic field (B) is the tesla (T). 1 T = 1 kg/(A·s²). Earth's magnetic field at the surface is roughly 5 × 10⁻⁵ T.": "",
  "Magnetic field lines outside a bar magnet go from:": "",
  "South pole to north pole": "",
  "Positive to negative": "",
  "North pole to south pole": "",
  "They form straight lines from the center outward": "",
  "By convention, magnetic field lines emerge from the north pole and enter the south pole outside the magnet. Inside the magnet, they go from south to north, forming continuous closed loops.": "",
  "If you break a bar magnet in half, you get:": "",
  "One magnetic piece and one non-magnetic piece": "",
  "One north pole piece and one south pole piece": "",
  "Two smaller magnets, each with its own north and south pole": "",
  "Two unmagnetized pieces": "",
  "Magnetic monopoles do not exist. Breaking a magnet always produces two complete magnets, each with a north and south pole. This is true no matter how many times you subdivide.": "",
  "The magnetic force on a moving charged particle is always:": "",
  "Parallel to the velocity": "",
  "In the direction of the electric field": "",
  "Parallel to the magnetic field": "",
  "Perpendicular to both the velocity and the magnetic field": "",
  "The magnetic force F = qv × B is always perpendicular to both v and B. Because it is perpendicular to velocity, it does no work and only changes the direction of motion.": "",
  "A current-carrying wire in a magnetic field experiences a force. What happens if the current is parallel to the magnetic field?": "",
  "Zero force": "",
  "Maximum force": "",
  "Oscillating force": "",
  "Force along the wire": "",
  "F = IL × B = ILB sin(θ). When current is parallel to B, θ = 0° and sin(0°) = 0, so the force is zero. Maximum force occurs when current is perpendicular to B.": "",
  "The magnetic field at the center of a long solenoid depends on:": "",
  "The current and the number of turns per unit length": "",
  "Only the radius of the solenoid": "",
  "Only the total number of turns": "",
  "The material of the wire only": "",
  "For a long solenoid, B = μ₀nI, where n is the number of turns per unit length and I is the current. The field is uniform inside and essentially zero outside.": "",
  "A charged particle moving perpendicular to a uniform magnetic field follows what path?": "",
  "A parabola": "",
  "A circle": "",
  "A straight line": "",
  "A spiral of decreasing radius": "",
  "Since the magnetic force is always perpendicular to velocity and constant in magnitude, it provides centripetal acceleration, causing the charge to move in a circle: r = mv/(qB).": "",
  "The right-hand rule for a straight current-carrying wire tells you that the magnetic field lines around the wire form:": "",
  "Radial lines pointing outward": "",
  "Concentric circles around the wire": "",
  "Straight lines parallel to the wire": "",
  "Spirals along the wire": "",
  "The magnetic field around a long straight current-carrying wire forms concentric circles. Point the right thumb in the direction of current, and the fingers curl in the direction of B.": "",
  "What is the magnitude of the magnetic force on a proton (q = 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C) moving at 3 × 10⁶ m/s perpendicular to a 0.5 T magnetic field?": "",
  "2.4 × 10⁻¹³ N": "",
  "4.8 × 10⁻¹³ N": "",
  "2.4 × 10⁻¹⁰ N": "",
  "7.5 × 10⁻¹⁴ N": "",
  "F = qvB sin(90°) = 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ × 3 × 10⁶ × 0.5 = 2.4 × 10⁻¹³ N.": "",
  "What is a 'magnetic dipole'?": "",
  "A point charge at rest, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "A single moving charge, despite what intuition might initially": "",
  "An object with a north and south pole, such as a bar magnet or current loop": "",
  "An isolated magnetic north pole, especially during periods": "",
  "A magnetic dipole has both a north and south pole, like a bar magnet or a current-carrying loop. Magnetic monopoles (isolated north or south poles) have never been observed.": "",
  "What does 'ferromagnetism' mean?": "",
  "A weak repulsion from magnetic fields exhibited by all materials": "",
  "The strong magnetic behavior in materials like iron, where atomic magnetic moments align cooperatively to produce large net magnetization": "",
  "Magnetism generated solely by electric current": "",
  "The magnetism of superconductors": "",
  "Ferromagnetism occurs in materials (iron, nickel, cobalt) where magnetic domains—regions of aligned atomic magnetic moments—can align to produce strong magnetization.": "",
  "What is 'magnetic flux'?": "",
  "The product of the magnetic field and the area through which it passes, accounting for the angle: Φ = BA cos(θ)": "",
  "The magnetic field strength at a point when considering all relevant magnetic factors": "",
  "The current in a solenoid when considering all relevant magnetic factors": "",
  "The force on a charge in a magnetic field, particularly in the context of magnetic": "",
  "Magnetic flux Φ_B = BA cos(θ) measures the total magnetic field passing through a surface, where θ is the angle between B and the surface normal. It is measured in webers (Wb).": "",
  "What does 'permeability of free space' (μ₀) refer to?": "",
  "The magnetic field of Earth": "",
  "A constant that relates magnetic field to the current producing it in vacuum: μ₀ = 4π × 10⁻⁷ T·m/A": "",
  "The ability of a vacuum to store electric energy": "",
  "The speed of light in vacuum": "",
  "The permeability of free space μ₀ = 4π × 10⁻⁷ T·m/A is the proportionality constant in equations for magnetic fields produced by currents in vacuum.": "",
  "What is the 'right-hand rule' for magnetic force?": "",
  "Use the right hand to determine the direction of electric field lines": "",
  "Point your right thumb in the direction of the magnetic field to find the force": "",
  "The rule states that force is always to the right of the velocity": "",
  "Point fingers of the right hand in the direction of velocity (or current), curl them toward B, and the thumb points in the direction of force on a positive charge": "",
  "For F = qv × B, point the right hand's fingers along v, curl them toward B, and the extended thumb gives the force direction for a positive charge. For negative charges, reverse the direction.": "",
  "What is a 'solenoid'?": "",
  "A coil of wire carrying current that produces a nearly uniform magnetic field inside, similar to a bar magnet": "",
  "A device that converts light to electricity, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "A device that stores electric charge without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "A type of resistor, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these solenoid dynamics": "",
  "A solenoid is a helical coil of wire that, when current flows through it, produces a uniform magnetic field inside (B = μ₀nI). It behaves like a bar magnet with defined north and south poles.": "",
  "What does 'diamagnetism' mean?": "",
  "A very weak repulsion from magnetic fields, present in all materials, caused by induced changes in electron orbits": "",
  "A strong attraction to external magnetic fields": "",
  "Permanent magnetization of a material": "",
  "Magnetism caused only by nuclear spins": "",
  "Diamagnetism is a weak repulsive effect present in all materials. An external field induces tiny opposing magnetic moments in atoms. In most materials it is masked by stronger paramagnetic or ferromagnetic effects.": "",
  "What is 'paramagnetism'?": "",
  "The magnetic effect of electric current in a wire according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "A weak attraction to magnetic fields caused by the partial alignment of existing magnetic moments in an external field": "",
  "A property of superconductors only within the broader context of field analysis": "",
  "A type of permanent magnetism, as conventional field theory would suggest": "",
  "Paramagnetic materials (like aluminum, platinum) have atoms with unpaired electrons that partially align with an external field, producing a weak attraction. The effect disappears when the field is removed.": "",
  "What is the 'Curie temperature'?": "",
  "The temperature at which a gas becomes a liquid": "",
  "The temperature above which a ferromagnetic material loses its permanent magnetism and becomes paramagnetic": "",
  "Absolute zero": "",
  "The temperature at which a superconductor works best": "",
  "The Curie temperature is the critical temperature above which thermal agitation disrupts the alignment of magnetic domains, and a ferromagnet becomes paramagnetic. For iron, it is about 770°C.": "",
  "What does 'magnetic domain' mean?": "",
  "A small region within a ferromagnetic material where atomic magnetic moments are aligned in the same direction": "",
  "A unit of magnetic flux under most circumstances involving magnetic": "",
  "The area of a magnetic field that is strongest, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "The region of space outside a magnet when considering all relevant magnetic factors": "",
  "A magnetic domain is a microscopic region in a ferromagnetic material where the atomic magnetic moments are aligned. When domains align with each other, the material becomes magnetized.": "",
  "An MRI machine uses a superconducting magnet with a field strength of 3 T. A hydrogen proton (q = 1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ C, m = 1.67 × 10⁻²⁷ kg) precesses in this field. What is the cyclotron frequency of the proton?": "",
  "About 12.8 MHz": "",
  "About 128 MHz": "",
  "About 64 MHz": "",
  "About 1.28 GHz": "",
  "Cyclotron frequency f = qB/(2πm) = (1.6 × 10⁻¹⁹ × 3)/(2π × 1.67 × 10⁻²⁷) = 4.8 × 10⁻¹⁹/(1.05 × 10⁻²⁶) ≈ 4.57 × 10⁷ Hz. The actual proton Larmor frequency in a 3T MRI is about 128 MHz (using the precise gyromagnetic ratio).": "",
  "A compass needle points roughly toward geographic north. This is because Earth's magnetic field:": "",
  "Is generated by permanent magnets in Earth's crust": "",
  "Has its magnetic south pole near the geographic north pole, attracting the compass's north-seeking pole": "",
  "Has its magnetic north pole at the geographic north pole": "",
  "Is caused by electric charges in the atmosphere": "",
  "Earth's magnetic south pole is near the geographic North Pole. A compass's north-seeking pole is attracted toward this magnetic south pole, which is why it points roughly northward.": "",
  "A wire carrying 5 A of current is placed in a 0.2 T magnetic field perpendicular to the wire. If the wire is 0.3 m long, what force acts on it?": "",
  "3.0 N": "",
  "30 N": "",
  "0.3 N": "",
  "0.03 N": "",
  "F = BIL sin(90°) = 0.2 × 5 × 0.3 = 0.3 N. This is the principle behind electric motors.": "",
  "A mass spectrometer separates ions by injecting them into a magnetic field where they follow circular paths. Two ions have the same charge and speed but different masses. The heavier ion follows:": "",
  "A larger circle": "",
  "The same circle": "",
  "A smaller circle": "",
  "The radius of circular motion is r = mv/(qB). For the same q, v, and B, larger mass m gives a larger radius. This is how mass spectrometers distinguish isotopes.": "",
  "A charged particle enters a region where both electric and magnetic fields exist. The particle travels in a straight line without deflection. This is possible when:": "",
  "The particle has no charge in most scenarios involving particle factors": "",
  "The fields are parallel to each other, particularly in the context of particle": "",
  "Both fields are zero according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "The electric force and magnetic force are equal in magnitude and opposite in direction": "",
  "In a velocity selector, E and B are arranged so qE = qvB. Only particles with speed v = E/B pass through undeflected. Faster or slower particles are deflected.": "",
  "An electromagnet in a junkyard lifts cars using a solenoid with 500 turns per meter carrying 200 A. What is the magnetic field inside? (μ₀ = 4π × 10⁻⁷ T·m/A)": "",
  "About 0.126 T": "",
  "About 12.6 T": "",
  "About 1.26 T": "",
  "About 0.013 T": "",
  "B = μ₀nI = 4π × 10⁻⁷ × 500 × 200 = 4π × 10⁻² ≈ 0.126 T. A ferromagnetic core would multiply this dramatically.": "",
  "Maglev trains float above the track using magnetic levitation. If a 40,000 kg train needs to be levitated against gravity (g = 10 m/s²), what upward magnetic force must the system provide?": "",
  "40,000 N": "",
  "4,000,000 N": "",
  "400,000 N": "",
  "4,000 N": "",
  "To levitate, the magnetic force must equal gravity: F = mg = 40,000 × 10 = 400,000 N (400 kN).": "",
  "A student holds a strong permanent magnet near a CRT (cathode ray tube) television and notices the image distorts with swirling colors. This occurs because:": "",
  "The magnet reverses the polarity of the electrical signal": "",
